following best describes the genetic basis of Huntington disease?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["X-linked dominant inheritance with gene deletion","Mitochondrial inheritance with DNA depletion","Autosomal dominant inheritance with variable penetrance","Autosomal recessive inheritance with point mutation","Autosomal dominant inheritance with CAG repeat expansion"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutosomal dominant inheritance with CAG repeat expansion\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes Huntington disease genetics. The condition is caused by an expanded CAG trinucleotide repeat sequence in the huntingtin gene on chromosome 4. The disease shows complete penetrance, meaning that all individuals who inherit the mutation will develop symptoms if they live long enough.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EX-linked dominant inheritance with gene deletion\u003C/strong\u003E - The huntingtin gene is located on chromosome 4, not the X chromosome\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMitochondrial inheritance with DNA depletion\u003C/strong\u003E - Huntington disease is not caused by mitochondrial DNA mutations\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutosomal dominant inheritance with variable penetrance\u003C/strong\u003E - While inheritance is autosomal dominant, penetrance is complete rather than variable\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAutosomal recessive inheritance with point mutation\u003C/strong\u003E - Huntington disease is dominantly inherited and involves trinucleotide repeats, not point mutations\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe number of CAG repeats influences disease severity and age of onset, with longer repeat lengths generally correlating with earlier onset. Normal alleles have 35 or fewer repeats, while disease-causing alleles typically have 40 or more repeats.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Huntington disease is caused by CAG trinucleotide repeat expansion in the huntingtin gene on chromosome 4.","The disease shows autosomal dominant inheritance with complete penetrance.","Longer CAG repeat lengths correlate with earlier age of disease onset."],"references":["Turnpenny PD, Ellard S. Emery\u0027s Elements of Medical Genetics E-Book: Elsevier Health Sciences; 2011","Chial, H. (2008) Huntington\u0027s disease: The discovery of the Huntingtin gene. Nature Education 1(1):71. Available at: https://www.nature.com/scitable/topicpage/huntington-s-disease-the-discovery-of-the-851/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63385"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17255"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"63385","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/63385"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-08T20:34:38+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-08T20:36:52+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9945"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77907"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes"